english:
  title: Reply to a Letter from Xu Zhou's Administrator Shi Pu
  author: Choe Chi-won
  language: eng
  text: "The sixteenth day of the sixth month. I humbly submit my response. Your Excellency has graciously sent a lengthy letter, and further submitted official documents. Upon careful examination of your intentions, I find they touch upon many matters—as though words spoken in jest before now warrant serious consideration. Surely this would astonish those who hear it. Though I recognize the strength of your forces and the vigor of your armies, what remedy exists when falsehood weighs upon the mind? Moreover, Si State was formerly under your jurisdiction, yet its new administrative designation came not from a prefect's arbitrary decision, but from directives of the imperial court itself.\n\nFormerly, I alone preserved integrity and loyalty, earning a place among the garrison commanders, with honors transmitted to the valiant. Of late, we have become entangled in mutual enmity, yet I have adhered to the laws of the realm, walking the straight path alone, holding firm this precarious city. I have tasted bitterness in contention, nor do I shrink from death itself—this follows the ancient principle: better to be a loyal ghost than a treacherous minister.\n\nConsider your illustrious position—blessed with the authority of one who restores nations and the martial prowess of the valiant, you have brought ease to a weary people and satisfaction to the multitudes. When the sage-king Gou Jian shared his wine equally among all, and when Zang Hong distributed his thin gruel with abundance to spare, should you not likewise disperse three years' stores to meet a single day's need? The small can overcome the great; the humble can match the laborious. This is far different from those who build houses only to farm, who close their doors and sweep their steps.\n\nYet your recent letter speaks thus: \"Si State alone blocks the Huai River, fortifying itself so that the four directions are obstructed and the many roads cannot pass. Moreover, it constantly makes false accusations against the court. Now officers within the city secretly come to plot. If only you would show some military strength, then peace might be secured.\" \n\nBut in human affairs, nothing surpasses self-knowledge. Last year, though you restrained your ambitions, you pursued advancement with great urgency. You suddenly displayed the vigor of the bold and achieved the authority of a loyal administrator, receiving repeatedly the grace of the realm and being entrusted with distant provincial governance. How then can you elevate yourself while diminishing others, claiming righteousness for yourself while condemning others? Should you inadvertently create suspicion, as did Lin Xiangru, you will ultimately share the blame borne by the Ji clan.\n\nThe prolonged obstruction of the Huai River and blockage of the roads—these result from your prefecture sending forth troops, not from Si State creating barriers. This truth is known far and wide. Last summer's invasion began early. You summoned ants from the marshes and arrayed tigers upon the mountains. To rescue those bound by righteousness, one cannot avoid skilled warfare. Thus we planned a modest campaign to save those hanging in desperate straits.\n\nYou are not like Xun Wu, unable to earn the glory of accepting surrender. I confess, like Lü Bu, a shortcoming in my words of reconciliation. Si State reports only facts—how could this be slander? Though I am ashamed to be called a trusted friend, I have long recommended the worthy and recorded imperial decrees for your consideration, believing you would understand. Yet who could have foreseen that beyond our hopes, you would suddenly initiate conflict, that armies would march and your borders would tremble repeatedly?\n\nYour claim that Si State's officers frequently come to plot—this is merely honeyed deception spread through lengthy documents. All know these are cunning provocations; who would be deceived? The court, recognizing that your person stands in a mighty city with abundant military resources, entrusted you with the transport of supplies, hoping you would cooperate. If you would merely restrain your forces, the roads for provisions would flow freely. Yet now you suddenly declare: \"The court's will is to seize Xu and Si territories\"—and send forth armies. The intent is unclear.\n\nIf you truly train your troops with valor and repay your sovereign with loyalty, why not personally lead the entire army to eliminate the great bandits, establishing extraordinary merit to repay extraordinary grace? Instead, knowing of my two western campaigns and plans to cross northward, you invaded Si's borders and violated the Huai region, betraying the realm's favor and bringing calamity to its districts. That brigand forces have fortunately delayed our campaign is mere chance. How can I fathom your true intentions? What fault have I committed to deserve the sovereign's rebuke?\n\nYour words proliferate in details but fail to address the root. Your recent letter further claims: \"Lu State and Hai State have both rebelled; repeatedly they have submitted in sincerity, yet you send no acknowledgment of their words.\" You force the appearance of benevolence upon paper, but though your face may show no shame, can your heart find peace? In these eastern and river regions, wickedness has chanced to gather, and heterodoxy has arisen. These are not the timid folk of old—bound by common purpose, they are all followers of the robber Zhi.\n\nYou already hold high office; do not entertain dangerous schemes. Guard the imperial edicts yourself—why such elaborate pretense? I have repeatedly carried military provisions and rescued Lin-Huai to distinguish the loyal from the treacherous and preserve steadfast purpose. It is precisely because Si State, though small, has never been discourteous like the state of Qi, and has possessed the reasoned words of Zhanyan. When I have received appeals of distress, I have responded with benevolence and righteousness.\n\nI merely entreat you: briefly set aside your remaining anger and consider deeper strategy. First manifest your loyalty to the realm; do not hastily wage war against neighbors. The imperial decree you received requested harmony with our loyal commanders—this shows the court's regard for you and desire to dispel any grievance. As a loyal minister, you must reflect carefully: long preserve the welfare of the people and swiftly recall your soldiers. Should you fail your sovereign's commands and ignore the people's will, obstructing military roads and encroaching on neighboring lands, then know that one soldier can match your thousand. You will surely witness how wounded birds startle easily and cornered beasts still fight. Regret cannot prevent what follows; danger already stands before you.\n\nMoreover, Si State bears the name of integrity while your garrison pursues the art of war; Si State alone follows the royal transformation while your garrison fabricates false documents. In comparing merit and fault, the right and wrong are clear. Therefore I dare submit this loyal counsel, hoping to prevent future troubles.\n\nIn this time when the sacred sovereign endures hardship and calamity remains unresolved, how can you bear to let the feudal lords again raise arms upon their lands? Speak bold truths rather than hollow flattery; consider the greater good rather than expose minor flaws. I trust that by this day's admonition, a future day will bring your gratitude. I pray you follow sincerity and preserve your honor unstained.\n\nI, your humble servant, bow my head in reverence."
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Si State (泗州) and the Huai River region were strategic locations during Tang Dynasty conflicts over power and territorial control.
  - key: ''
    value: References to historical figures like Gou Jian, Zang Hong, Xun Wu, and Lü Bu serve as moral exemplars and cautionary tales about loyalty, strategy, and reconciliation.
  - key: ''
    value: The letter employs classical allusions to frame Choe Chi-won's argument about duty to the realm versus local military ambitions.
